<TITLE> HomePage for Brian Harvey (bh@cs.Berkeley.EDU) </TITLE>

<!WA0><IMG SRC="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~bh/bh.gif"> <!WA1><IMG SRC="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~bh/info.gif">

<P>I teach many of the lower division (freshman and sophomore)
<!WA2><A HREF="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~bh/lowdiv.html">computer science courses</A>
at Berkeley.  I'm faculty advisor of the
<!WA3><A HREF="http://www.csua.berkeley.edu/">Computer Science
Undergraduate Association</A> and of the
<!WA4><A HREF="http://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/">Open Computing Facility</A>.

<P>I'm also interested in the use of computers in
pre-college education; I used to be a <!WA5><A HREF="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~bh/lsrhs.html">high school</A>
teacher, and I'm involved in the development of the Logo programming
language.

<P><!WA6><A HREF="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~bh/usermanual">Berkeley Logo</A>
is a freeware interpreter that I wrote along with
several students.  (Major contributors are Dan van Blerkom,
Michael Katz, and Doug Orleans.)  Click here to retrieve
the <STRONG>complete distribution</STRONG> archive for
<!WA7><A HREF="file://anarres.cs.berkeley.edu/pub/ucblogo/ucblogo.tar.Z">Unix</A>,
<!WA8><A HREF="file://anarres.cs.berkeley.edu/pub/ucblogo/blogo.exe">DOS</A>, or
<!WA9><A HREF="file://anarres.cs.berkeley.edu/pub/ucblogo/ucblogo.sea.hqx">Mac</A>,
complete with C source code.  (If you think Logo is just a graphics
language for little kids, check out a
<!WA10><A HREF="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~bh/logo-sample.html">sample program</A>
that should impress you.)

<P><!WA11><IMG SRC="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~bh/v1-tiny.gif">  <!WA12><IMG SRC="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~bh/v2-tiny.gif">  <!WA13><IMG SRC="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~bh/v3-tiny.gif">
<!WA14><IMG SRC="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~bh/csls-para.gif">

<UL>
<LI><CITE><!WA15><A HREF="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~bh/v1-toc.html">Intermediate Programming</A></CITE>,
a Logo programming text that concentrates on natural language
processing rather than the graphics most people associate with Logo.
<LI><CITE><!WA16><A HREF="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~bh/v2-toc.html">Projects, Styles, and Techniques</A></CITE>,
a collection of ten largeish Logo programs with commentary on the
structure and style of each.
<LI><CITE><!WA17><A HREF="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~bh/v3-toc.html">Advanced Topics</A></CITE>,
brief introductions to six college-level computer science topics.
</UL>

<P>The <CITE>Computer Science Logo Style</CITE> books are out of print,
but you can order a bound photocopy from
<!WA18><A HREF="http://nimrod.mit.edu/depts/document_services/mit-press.html">
MIT Document Services</A>.  The second edition should be published
early in 1997.

<P><!WA19><A HREF="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~bh/simply-toc.html"><!WA20><IMG SRC="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~bh/ss-poop.gif"></A><!WA21><IMG SRC="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~bh/simply.gif">

<P>I've written several <!WA22><A HREF="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~bh/papers.html">papers about
computers and education</A>.

<P>I'm a member of <!WA23><A
HREF="http://www.cpsr.org/dox/home.html">Computer
Professionals for Social Responsibility</A>,
<!WA24><A HREF="http://www.lpf.org/">the League for Programming Freedom</A>, and <!WA25><A
HREF="http://www.aclu.org/">the
American Civil Liberties Union</A>.

<H3>So, what do you do for fun, Brian?</H3>

<UL>
<LI>I visit the <!WA26><A HREF="http://www.exploratorium.edu/">Exploratorium</A>,
the world's best museum.
<LI>I watch the <!WA27><A
HREF="http://www.cs.cmu.edu/afs/cs.cmu.edu/user/clamen/misc/tv/Animaniacs/Animaniacs.html">
Animaniacs</A>, the only good thing on television.
<LI>I listen to 1964-1968 British rock, especially the 
<!WA28><A HREF="http://www.primenet.com/~dhaber/beatles.html">Beatles</A>.
<LI>I eat <!WA29><A
HREF="http://www.lysator.liu.se:7500/etexts/recept/us/potstickers.html">Chinese
food</A>.
<LI>I collect <!WA30><A HREF="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~bh/art.html">art</A> and
<!WA31><A HREF="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~bh/masks.html">masks</A>.  (Lots of bits in these links.)
</UL>

<P>Check out the <!WA32><A HREF="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~bh/turkey.html">world's best turkey
stuffing recipe</A>.

